When the **Fisher-information term \(\,\tfrac{\sigma^{2}}{2}I(p_{\sigma,t})\)** dominates the entropy balance (this happens for any fixed, \(t\!>\!0\) as \(\sigma\) grows, or for very short times with moderate \(\sigma\)) the density is still essentially a *Brownian blur* of the initial point set.  In that regime one may neglect the \(O(1)\) drift–divergence piece and use the explicit Brownian entropy formula:

\[
h(\sigma,t)\;\approx\;\frac{d}{2}\log\!\bigl(2\pi e\,\sigma^{2}t\bigr)\;+\;O(1).
\]

Divide by \(\log\sigma\;(>0)\):

\[
\boxed{\;
\frac{h(\sigma,t)}{\log\sigma}
     \;=\;
     \frac{d}{2}\,\frac{\log\bigl(\sigma^{2}\bigr)}{\log\sigma}
     \;+\; \frac{d}{2}\,\frac{\log(2\pi e t)}{\log\sigma}
     \;+\;O\!\Bigl(\frac1{\log\sigma}\Bigr)
     \;=\;
     d \;+\; O\!\Bigl(\tfrac{\log t}{\log\sigma}\Bigr).
\;}

Hence:

* **For large noise** (\(\sigma\!\to\!\infty\) with \(t\) fixed) \(\displaystyle\lim_{\sigma\to\infty}\tfrac{h(\sigma,t)}{\log\sigma}=d\).
* **For finite but big \(\sigma\)** the ratio is \(d\) up to a correction \(\bigl(d/2\bigr)\tfrac{\log(2\pi e t)}{\log\sigma}\), which is small whenever \(\log\sigma\gg\log t\).

So in the early, diffusion-dominated phase the entropy grows as though the state were simply a \(d\)-dimensional Gaussian of variance \(\sigma^{2}t\), and the “dimension proxy’’ \(h/\log\sigma\) sits essentially at its maximal value \(d\).

Using the **log-power path**  

\[
t(\sigma)\;=\;t_{\mathrm{mix}}\;+\;\bigl[\log(1/\sigma)\bigr]^{\beta},
\qquad 0<\beta<1 ,
\]

the chain-rule decomposition is  

\[
\underbrace{\frac{{\rm d}}{{\rm d}\log\sigma}h\bigl(\sigma,t(\sigma)\bigr)}
          _{\tilde D(\sigma)}
    \;=\;
    \underbrace{\frac{\partial h}{\partial\log\sigma}(\sigma,t)}
               _{\text{“direct” piece}}
    \;+\;
    \underbrace{\frac{\partial h}{\partial t}(\sigma,t)\;
                \frac{{\rm d}t}{{\rm d}\log\sigma}}
               _{\text{time-correction}},
\qquad t=t(\sigma).
\tag{1}
\]

Below is the explicit size of each term when \(\sigma\downarrow0\).

